<br>
Am I 100% for the big record companies?  No.  I haven't bought more than 3 CDs in the last few years.  Mostly because 98% of music avialable out there is crap...but that's an other story and totaly my opinion.  <br>
<br>
If you don't like their way of doing business, don't buy their product...but make sure that the &quot;small/indipendant&quot; company you are supporting isn't really run by the big guys.  Radio is a good idea gone corrupt...but you can't really blame the radio stations for wanting to play what's popular, can you?  You can't expect a company to make advertising money playing unknown European Techno bands, can you?  They're forced to play what people want to hear.  It's not really so much what the record company tells them as much as what the advertisers, listeners tell them.<br>
<br>
Have I gone to the propoganda sight?  Nope.  Will I?  Nope.  It's not unbiased, so I'm not going to waste my time there.  The music industry isn't an easy one to get into...nor is it guaranteed that you'll make any sort of money.  All the money you spend on a CD isn't going into the Exec's pockets.  There's alot of people who work for that company, and since it's in America, the folk who work there constantly want raises/time off etc.  You can't really expect them to lower their prices can you, with the demands of the American Worker?  (I'm American...not against the worker at all..just using this for explination's sake).  <br>
<br>
A tiny fraction of what you pay for a CD goes to the artist.  So every CD they sell counts.  If you like the artist, do them a favor and support them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zekspawn>Zekspawn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/27/03 2:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I hate the RIAA.  A lot.</span><hr size=1> Sorry..but about the copyright thing...you aren't downloading stuff from the 50's here..your downloading modern music. It's far from outdated. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ermok>Ermok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 610<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/27/03 8:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I hate the RIAA.  A lot.</span><hr size=1> What would have happened if the railroads had fought the airlines?  It is the exact same principal.  Airlines destroyed the railroads' success.  It demonstrates a trend that exorberantly profitable industries will eventually be put in check by new mediums.<br>
<br>
What is happening here is that we are dealing with a whole new medium.  While there are some similarities to existing precedents, the laws are being misinterpreted.  The technology has changed too rapidly for them to apply.<br>
<br>
There needs to be a new set of laws regarding digital material and DMCA does NOT count.  It is based in antiquated legal logic and is merely a tool bought by corporations to serve them in the court battles they foresaw.<br>
<br>
Free speech is not just the right to say what you want.  It is also the freedom to be exposed to what you want.  What governments are dealing with now in piracy is the wanton exchange of information.  History has shown that you cant put a stop to that.  Eventually restraints and punishments will lead to violent upheaval.<br>
<br>
This is basic economics and consumerism.  A market has opened up that is far superior at the task of getting products to consumers.  And as economics can predict, the older market will die.  Deep seated companies held by old grizzled mogols are unwilling to change.<br>
<br>
Everyone knows what the Kelly Blue Book is (a listing of used car values).  The company that printed it however, does 99% of their business online now.  They saw a more efficient way as the times changed and rather than attacking other online price consulting they put their name on their own service.<br>
<br>
Companies are trying that with 99 cent downloads.  It is a start but it will never catch on.  The reason... its a dollar per song.  At one point my collection would have been worth in excess of $5,000.  The price has to come down to something more reasonable, like 10 cents, for it to compete with the free market.  As of now, record companies only agree to such licensing because they will only accept equal compensation per song as CDs.<br>
<br>
Yes, I do have the audacity to tell recording companies to lay down and die.  Because they inevitably will.  Its not the future they are fighting, it is the established laws of economics in a free market.  <br>
<br>
Eventually the million dollar rock stars wont have so many million.  They main revenue will come from live entertainment and promotional deals.  It is just a mere fluke that the 20th century saw musicians become major social and financial powers where they had never been before in history.  The 21st is going to set them back to equilibrium. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fireandfury.org" target="top"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.fireandfury.org/ermoksig1.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eliezeroferudin>Eliezer of Erudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Order of Crimson Hands</span><br>  Posts: 1582<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/27/03 9:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=688.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I hate the RIAA.  A lot.</span><hr size=1> Actually, I would not mind one bit if this crippled the music industry and kept us from having to inundated by millions of fabricated pop stars.<br>
